  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, felt tension that can silence potential. As someone who grew up in a community where academic success was often tied to cultural identity, I've seen how the weight of expectations can make even capable students hesitate. When you're told, 'You're not cut out for this,' it doesn't matter if you're smart or hardworking—it becomes a psychological barrier. In my experience, the problem isn't just about individual performance but about systemic messaging that tells marginalized groups they don't belong. For instance, I remember a time when a student I taught in a community college hesitated to ask questions because they feared being labeled 'not good enough' in a math class. That moment was heartbreaking because it showed how stereotypes can manifest as self-doubt before any actual learning occurs. Addressing this isn't about fixing people—it's about changing the environment. We need to normalize vulnerability, celebrate diverse problem-solving styles, and create spaces where students feel safe to make mistakes. Schools and workplaces should implement inclusive curricula that highlight underrepresented voices in STEM and train educators to recognize and counter implicit biases. It's not a one-size-fits-all solution, but it's essential. If we don't act, we'll continue to lose talent before they even have a chance to shine.",
